<div class="container">
    <div>
        <h1 id="tutorial_graph">How to read graph visualizations</h1>
        <div class="row tutorialsection">
            <div class="col-sm">
                <p>In graph representations, a node having multiple edges connected to it means there is an implicit "and" logical
                    operation between what those edges represent.</p>
                <p>Starting to read from the x entity or a event node is the best way to read graph visualizations.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row tutorialsection">
            <div class="col-sm-8">
                <p>In graph visualizations, there are several types of nodes :</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Blue ones are entities.</li>
                    <li>Red ones are events.</li>
                    <li>Green ones provide additionnal information by connecting the others.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>There are also several types of edges :</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>is-a edges specify what is exactly an entity (x for instance) refers to.</li>
                    <li>event, subject and object edges specify the entities participating in an event.</li>
                    <li>conj edges connect the objects joined together by green nodes.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-sm-4">
                <img class="img-thumbnail mx-auto d-block" src="/images/examplegraph1.png" alt="">
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row tutorialsection">
            <div class="col-sm-4">
                <img class="img-thumbnail mx-auto d-block" src="/images/examplegraph2.png" alt="">
            </div>
            <div class="col-sm-8">
                <p>Red polygons are negation areas. They encompass the scope of the negation; everything in them has its meaning
                    reversed. For example, having a e node in a negation polygon means e does not exist.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row tutorialsection">
            <div class="col-sm-8">
                <p>Disjunction is represented by a new class of nodes : Yellow nodes. The yellow OR node is connected to either
                    possibilities presented by the disjunction.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-sm-4">
                <img class="img-thumbnail mx-auto d-block" src="/images/examplegraph3.png" alt="">
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
